et to the highest point of the waterfall, you will have to put up with some unpleasant physical conditions. There are five distinct portions of the falls. To get to the tallest falls, you will have to walk for about five kilometres through thick woods (the path isn't exactly in the best condition). If you make it there, though, you will be awestruck by the region's natural splendour. You won't only have a bird's-eye view of the city from this vantage point; you'll also be able to watch the water cascade down from a considerable height. However, you are recommended not to go to the highest point. The lower tiers of the waterfall are the ones most often explored by visitors who are not very physically fit. The nicest thing about the forest is that it is completely covered with trees that grow various herbs and spices, some of which may even be used for therapeutic purposes. You will be completely captivated by the whole region. If you have a passion for animals and the natural world, you could have the opportunity to see some birds or other wildlife creatures that are extinct or very uncommon. If you want to go on nature walks out there, you need to hire a local guide who will be able to assist you in safely finishing the excursion so that you can enjoy the experience. 3. Tali Shiva Temple Tali Shiva Temple is devoted to the Hindu god Shiva and is considered among the holiest places in Kozhikode. This temple was constructed in the fourteenth century by the Zamorins, and it is also the residence of Lord Ayappa. It is a widespread belief in Kozhikode that the spiritual purity of this temple is directly related to the city's economic success. There is a widespread belief among the faithful that Saint Parasuram was responsible for installing the main idol inside the temple. You will see that the idol is positioned like Sri Parasuram. This temple first came to the notice of the residents of Kozhikode some 1500 years ago. In addition to being covered in murals, these walls 